abstract={The global space market has been continuously growing in the last years; even during this deep economic crisis. It is just another symptom of the growing importance and maturity of the space sector. Indeed, many other sectors depend to some extent on satellite services, including finance, communication, transport, communication or military. This growing relevance of space-based services in our societies, although mostly unnoticed by citizens, has gathered attention from several types of attackers: from hacktivists such as Anonymous, to cyber-crooks or hostile governments. These groups of attackers are not equally attracted towards all space missions. As an example; earth observation or military missions will gain more attention from hostile governments, communication missions will typically be more attractive for cyber-crooks as long as they can obtain benefit from them; and virtually anything with a minimum notoriety will be a target for hacktivists. Also, typically, the skills and resources of the different types of attackers will differ significantly, with cyber-armies clearly on top. Few people deny today that cybersecurity has to be carefully considered in current and future space missions. Yet, not all missions are exposed to the same threats or present the same vulnerabilities; quoting Sun Tzu in the book 'Art of War': "If you know your enemies and know yourself, you will not be imperiled in a hundred battles. if you do not know your enemies nor yourself, you will be imperiled in every single battle." Consequently, a deep knowledge of the attacker groups' interests and skills together with a deep understanding of the mission business, its value-not only for the organization but also for third parties-, its feared events, and its vulnerabilities is crucial to define safeguards that effectively address the cyber-security risks faced by the mission. Performing this kind of analysis is complex and requires special knowledge and skills. Doing it for each